Tolerate binaries without Go module build info instead of panicking.

helm v4 derives default chart .Capabilities and its reported kube-client
version from the k8s.io/client-go entry in the binary's Go module build
info. Bazel/rules_go binaries carry no module build info, so
pkg/chart/common panics in init() (every command dies at startup) and
internal/version slog.Errors on every run. Fall back to the same stable
capabilities helm substitutes for test builds and leave the decorative
version string empty; hauler stores and serves charts as artifacts and
never renders against these defaults.

diff --git a/pkg/chart/common/capabilities.go b/pkg/chart/common/capabilities.go
--- a/pkg/chart/common/capabilities.go
+++ b/pkg/chart/common/capabilities.go
@@ -155 +155,5 @@ func makeDefaultCapabilities() (*Capabilities, error) {
-		return nil, fmt.Errorf("failed to retrieve k8s.io/client-go version: %w", err)
+		// Binaries built without Go module build info (e.g. Bazel/rules_go)
+		// cannot resolve the client-go version at runtime; fall back to the
+		// same stable capabilities test builds use instead of panicking in
+		// this package's init.
+		return newCapabilities(kubeVersionMajorTesting, kubeVersionMinorTesting)
diff --git a/internal/version/version.go b/internal/version/version.go
--- a/internal/version/version.go
+++ b/internal/version/version.go
@@ -91 +91,2 @@ func Get() BuildInfo {
-			slog.Error("failed to retrieve k8s.io/client-go version", slog.Any("error", err))
+			// No Go module build info (e.g. Bazel/rules_go builds); the
+			// version is decorative here, so degrade without log noise.
